text:
Nigericin is an &lt;a href="antibiotic"&gt;antibiotic&lt;/a&gt; derived from "&lt;a href="Streptomyces%20hygroscopicus"&gt;Streptomyces hygroscopicus&lt;/a&gt;". Its isolation was described in the 1950s, and in 1968 the structure could be elucidated by &lt;a href="X-ray%20crystallography"&gt;X-ray crystallography&lt;/a&gt;. The structure and properties of nigericin are similar to the &lt;a href="antibiotic"&gt;antibiotic&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="monensin"&gt;monensin&lt;/a&gt;. Commercially it is obtained as a byproduct, or contaminant, at the fermentation of &lt;a href="Geldanamycin"&gt;Geldanamycin&lt;/a&gt;. It is also called Polyetherin A, Azalomycin M, Helixin C, Antibiotic K178, Antibiotic X-464.
Nigericin acts as an H+, K+, Pb2+ &lt;a href="ionophore"&gt;ionophore&lt;/a&gt;. Most commonly it is an &lt;a href="antiporter"&gt;antiporter&lt;/a&gt; of H+ and K+. 
In the past nigericin was used as an antibiotic active against &lt;a href="gram%20positive"&gt;gram positive&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="bacteria"&gt;bacteria&lt;/a&gt;. It inhibits the &lt;a href="Golgi%20apparatus"&gt;Golgi&lt;/a&gt; functions in Eukaryotic cells. Its ability to induce K+ efflux also makes it a potent activator of the &lt;a href="NALP3"&gt;NLRP3&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="inflammasome"&gt;inflammasome&lt;/a&gt;
